# migrated from tests/cases/equality.chat (gen346, hermetic + isolated)
[mock hermetic]
!set PARROT0_BASE=
!set PARROT0_SESSION=
!set PARROT0_WORLD_FACTS=0
!set PARROT0_LANG=en
!reset

[test equality]
# Generation 292: EQUALITY CHAIN (basic-chat cat.7 prompt 124), the last cat.7 red.
# "a=b, b=c, what is a" -> a equals b and c. Equality is an EQUIVALENCE relation
# (reflexive, symmetric, transitive), so the value of a is its whole equivalence
# class. Unlike gen291's strict order, symmetry makes the relation cyclic — as a
# solver rule eq($X,$Y):-eq($Y,$X) it makes enumeration chase cycles — so the class
# is computed by a bounded connected-components walk over the stated equalities.
# The wh-query "what is <X>" is answered with the OTHER members of X's class.

# Prompt 124, verbatim.
> a=b, b=c, what is a
< b and c.
# Symmetric: querying the middle term returns the ends.
> a=b, b=c, what is b
< a and c.
# Separate components: a's class is {a,b}; c=d is a DIFFERENT class, so not listed.
> a=b, c=d, what is a
< b.
# A longer chain: querying the far end reaches the whole class (in walk order).
> a=b, b=c, c=d, what is d
< c, b and a.
# Not hijacked: a bare "what is X" with no equality is left to normal handling.
> what is a?
< I don't understand that yet.

